#Colorindo a saída
#print("\033[txtcolorm") <-- Sintáxe


 #Color e Value
'''Default	0
   Black	30 
   Red	31
   Green	32
   Yellow	33
   Blue	34  
   Purple	35
   Cyan	36
   White	37'''

print('''Welcome to your adventure simulator
I am going to ask you a bunch of 
questions and then create an epic
story with you as the star!''')
print()

name = input(str('What is your name? - '))
enemy = input(str("What is your worst enemy's? - "))
superpower = input(str('What is your superpower? - '))
country = input(str('Where country do you alive? - '))
food = input(str('What is your favorite food? - '))
color = input(str('What is your favorite color? - '))
print()

print(f'''\033[36mHello Mr{name} Your ability to {superpower} and your favorite color {color}, will make sure you never have \033[37mto look at {enemy} again. 
Go eat {food} as you walk down the streets of {country} and use {superpower} for good and not evil!''')


Considerações Finais: Podemos colorir de forma padrão pelo python com a seguinte sintáxe --> \033[NúmeroDaCorm
                                                                                             \033[33m
Temos tambem codigos como o TermColor que tambem ajuda a colorir a saída do programa, além de outras formatações específicas.
